               <desc type= "building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000214-2">In 1966, just about twelve years after the discovery of the monastery, <term ref="/place/000066">Nanchan Monastery</term> went through a severe earthquake. Nevertheless, architectural historians converted the calamity to an opportunity to study the buildings inside piece by piece (Steinhardt 2004, 235).</p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000214-3">Slightly less famous than the <term ref="/place/000169">Foguang Monastery Great East Hall</term>, the great hall at Nanchan Monastery is the earliest extant timber-frame building in China (Chai 1999A, 353). It is dated to 782 by an inscription on an interior <term ref="/keyword/k000139">level cross beam 平梁</term>, saying that “…[the building is] reconstructed in the third year of the Tang Jianzhong reign period （唐建中三年 782)” (Qi and Chai 1980, 61).</p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000214-4">Three-bays-wide both across the front façade and in-depth, Nanchan Monastery great hall is almost a perfect square in plan. The building itself has a single-eaves <term ref="/keyword/k000143">hip-gable roof</term> covered by grey <term ref="/keyword/k000109">barrel tiles</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000104">plate tiles</term>. Either simple struts or no supports at all are present on top of the columns at the great hall of the Nanchan Monastery to support the weight of the roof (Steinhardt 2004, 325).</p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000214-5">Around the building, there are twelve extant <term ref="/keyword/k000111">eaves columns 簷柱</term>, each slightly inclining inward <term ref="/keyword/k000006">(cejiao 側角)</term> and set into a stone column base (Gao 2001, 16). The three rectilinear pillars are the original ones made in the Tang dynasty, and the nine round pillars were replacements of the first year of the Yuanyou reign period in <term ref="/keyword/k000055">Northern Song dynasty</term> (元祐元年, 1086) (Steindhart 2004, 235). The pillars are connected by <term ref="/keyword/k000038">lan’e 闌額</term> on the top without <term ref="/keyword/k000067">pupaifang 普拍枋</term> above them (ZGWWTDJ 2006, 579). Like most other Chinese timber-frame structures, Nanchan Monastery great hall adhered to a modular system, however not precisely. Determined by dimensions of the <term ref="/keyword/k000019">bracket set 斗栱</term>, the module of the great hall is approximately 26 by 17 centimeters, which places it at fourth rank in Yingzao fashi 營造法式 (Steinhardt 2004, 235).</p>
                  
                  <p source="#bibl000214-6">Nanchan Monastery great hall was almost 1200 years old and severely weathered when it was found. Many of the building’s timber components had split, and some of them were already seriously decayed. After the two earthquakes in 1964 and 1966, a variety of the wood components were shaken out of the ortise holes 卯眼 and nearly ruptured (Chai 1999A, 354). In 1974, the restoration project of the great hall officially started, and it strictly conformed to the principle of “restoring to the original state or preserve the current state” (Chai 1999B, 361) The restoration team consolidated the important structural components such as the eaves pillars 簷柱, lan’e 闌額, shuatou 耍頭 that are the timbers joined through the <term ref="/keyword/k000156">linggong 令栱</term>, <term ref="/keyword/k000017">T-beams 丁栿</term>，and chashou 叉手 on pingliang 平梁 by adding ironworks in well-concealed positions(Chai 1999B, 366-367). 
                  </p>
